  "text": "The dynamic floor field D is just the virtual trace left by the pedestrians (see Sec. 3). It is modified by the presence of pedestrians and has its own dynamics, i.e. diffusion and decay. Usually the dynamic floor field is used to model a (\"longranged\") attractive interaction between the particles. Each pedestrian leaves a \"trace\", i.e. the floor field of occupied cells is increased. Explicit examples where such an interaction is relevant are given in Part II [CITATION_1] . The dynamic floor field is also subject to diffusion and decay which leads to a dilution and finally the vanishing of the trace after some time.",
